  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2554813885" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2554813885" />
    <a title="Stephanie Kline" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6801337-stephanie-kline"><img alt="Stephanie Kline" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624976156p2/6801337.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2554813885?book_show_action=true">Oct 11, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephanie Kline" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephanie Kline" href="/user/show/6801337-stephanie-kline">Stephanie Kline</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2554813885" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12550874371786916746">This was a great second novel in Nora’s Sign of Seven trilogy. It built on really nicely from the first book, “Blood Brothers”, and focused on two characters I really, really liked – Layla and Fox. <br/><br/>Layla came to Hawkins Hollow on a whim – leaving her comfortable, successful life in New York because of recurring nightmares that led her to this quaint, yet creepy, little Maryland town. Once she arrives in book one (not knowing what she’s doing there) she meets the others – Fox, Cal, Gage, Quinn, a</span>
  <span id="freeText12550874371786916746" style="display:none">This was a great second novel in Nora’s Sign of Seven trilogy. It built on really nicely from the first book, “Blood Brothers”, and focused on two characters I really, really liked – Layla and Fox. <br /><br />Layla came to Hawkins Hollow on a whim – leaving her comfortable, successful life in New York because of recurring nightmares that led her to this quaint, yet creepy, little Maryland town. Once she arrives in book one (not knowing what she’s doing there) she meets the others – Fox, Cal, Gage, Quinn, and Cybil. She then learns that the Hollow is plagued by a demonic force that has (for some reason) lured her there. Somehow, she knows she needs to stay to research the mystery of the town and to help her new friends defeat the darkness that threatens them all. <br /><br />Fox, however, has known all too well about the darkness of the Hollow since that fateful tenth birthday in the woods with Cal and Gage. On that day, they’d made a blood brothers pact at the Pagan Stone – the stone of town legend next to the haunted lake. Ever since, the three men have watched their town become threatened every seventh July during their birthday week, and this year, they know they need to stop it once and for all – before it claims the lives of people they love. <br /><br />This story deepens the friendships and relationships between all six of these wonderful characters. Layla and Fox have great chemistry, which I loved reading about. While Layla is shy and sweet – and certainly unsure about her role in this whole mess – Fox is self-assured and confident, but not in that annoying alpha-male way. He’s gentle with her, and their relationship develops naturally and sweetly. I loved the element of Layla working as Fox’s assistant in his legal office, and the witty, entertaining conversations they had throughout the book. <br /><br />The research element of this book was heavy, I have to say. They’re all figuring out more and more why the town is the way it is, and how its history unfolded almost 400 years ago. Slowly, they realize that they ALL might be more intricately connected to the Hollow than any of them had realized. Because of all this research and discussion about history, the middle portion of the book did get a little bogged down. This book wasn’t nearly as creepy as the first – with far fewer spine-chilling scenes. This was more about story development, which – while it absolutely has its place – was slightly less entertaining than the creep factor of book one. <br /><br />All in all, I really liked it. I loved Layla and Fox, and enjoyed all the new details that emerged. But I hope book three takes another turn towards the creepy!</span>
  <a data-text-id="12550874371786916746" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

