        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2476907477" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13779257848834951537">#2 in the Sign of Seven Trilogy<br/><br/>This book picks up right where the first book left off, but this time focusing on Fox and Layla. With July approaching, the 6 friends try to find out more about the Seven, the main characters from hundreds of years ago, and what they can do to defeat the demon. Layla seems to be the demon&apos;s focus, perhaps because she was the most recent to join the group and is perceived as the weakest. But she and Fox have gotten romantically close now, so she definitely has backu</span>
  <span id="freeText13779257848834951537" style="display:none">#2 in the Sign of Seven Trilogy<br /><br />This book picks up right where the first book left off, but this time focusing on Fox and Layla. With July approaching, the 6 friends try to find out more about the Seven, the main characters from hundreds of years ago, and what they can do to defeat the demon. Layla seems to be the demon's focus, perhaps because she was the most recent to join the group and is perceived as the weakest. But she and Fox have gotten romantically close now, so she definitely has backup, and they can work together to sense what's going on around them. The demon makes several attempts to hurt the group, but as long as they stick together, they are strong. When Cybil comes up with a plan for a blood oath, they face the bad guy at the Pagan Stone again. Actually, most of this book was about the romance between Fox and Layla, which was fine with me. Against the backdrop of the upcoming Seven, their coming together seems even more poignant. Fox is so cute, a loving and caring guy from a very tight family. And Layla is intelligent and sensible, although she tends to overreact to Fox's protectiveness. There's an exciting scene at the end, but it's clear that the resolution won't come until the next and last book of the trilogy. Which left me feeling a bit let-down and somewhat incomplete at the end. But I look forward to Gage and Cybil's story. Well read by Marie Caliendo. There were clear differences between the voices, and I particularly liked her Cybil voice. Quinn's voice definitely fit her personality, but it was annoyingly perky. Great job.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13779257848834951537" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


