  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_507250186" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/507250186" />
    <a title="Lydia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4691270-lydia"><img alt="Lydia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624197665p2/4691270.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/507250186?book_show_action=true">Jan 15, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lydia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lydia" href="/user/show/4691270-lydia">Lydia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4691270-lydia?shelf=sign-of-7">sign-of-7</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer507250186&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer507250186" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5468919699865245542"><i>“It seems to me it’s most important to go after what you want when there’s madness going on. I’m asking you to think about it. More, I guess I’m asking you to think about something you haven’t yet. Staying. Open the shop, manage my office, found a nudist colony, or take up macrame, I don’t care as long as it makes you happy. But I want you to think about staying, Layla, not just to destroy ancient fucking evil, but to live. To have a life, with me. Put THIS in one of your slots. I’m in love with</i></span>
  <span id="freeText5468919699865245542" style="display:none"><i>“It seems to me it’s most important to go after what you want when there’s madness going on. I’m asking you to think about it. More, I guess I’m asking you to think about something you haven’t yet. Staying. Open the shop, manage my office, found a nudist colony, or take up macrame, I don’t care as long as it makes you happy. But I want you to think about staying, Layla, not just to destroy ancient fucking evil, but to live. To have a life, with me. Put THIS in one of your slots. I’m in love with you. Completely, absolutely, no-turning-back in love with you. We could build something good, and solid, and real. Something that makes every day count. That’s what I want. So you think about it, and when you know, you tell me what you want.” - Fox O'Dell</i><br><br>Once in a while you come across a couple in a romance novel that is just meant to be. Being a major Nora Roberts fan, I can say without a doubt that I have seen my fair share of such fictional couples. But, like I said, there are times when, even if it's not their time yet, two of the characters just click together, and you know, hands down, they'll take a tumble if not something more.<br><br>Fox O'Dell and Layla Darnell of The Hollow were such a couple. The hippie lawyer and the quiet, reserved boutique manager just hit it off from the very first book, and it was easy for them to pick it up a notch in the second. Well, at least for Fox - Layla was really anal when it came to details and all that, something that I couldn't decide whether it would frustrate the man to death, or compliment him as he looked like he needed some serious mothering in his personal life...<br><br>The plot concerning the Big Evil Bastard doesn't exactly escalate in this book, if you except the new info the guys hid in the first one, like the whole deal with Carly, Fox's dead ex, and the twist that Ann Hawkins was giving birth to her triplets the very moment Lazarus Twisse and Giles Dent had their showdown. But I guess we can consider it their own personal lull, as they did at the beginning of the book, to charge and regroup, to plot and just find something to take a hold on to in order to have even the slightest idea of what they're supposed to be doing. It would have been easier, though, if Layla wasn't so negative on almost everything new around her, or Gage was more willing and patient to the whole "team theme". Especially Gage. I understand his point, this thing has taken long enough, and they have already entered the countdown phase, but does he have to be so damn rude and pessimistic? Sure, it could be excused, but lashing out on all of them, or saying that Cybil's premonitions were just nightmares wasn't exactly helping either...<br><br>There were parts, of course, that were pretty much spooky. Not at the same level they were in the first book. Because by now we're used to Twisse's creepy ways of freaking them out, and it actually comes out as usual and normal. But the part where Fox nearly died from Block's attack (damn you to all nine Hells and back, Derrick Napper!), or when they were all divided and attacked at the same time by their worst fears and nightmares... well, those ones were like horror movie clips, vivid, and altogether terrifying...<br><br>Fact is, though, that I laughed more than screamed when reading it. Fox has a way to make everything sound so funny, even when he's angry, and the O'Dell family is adorable. His attachment with his fleeing office manager, Mrs. Hawbaker, and how he kept putting dollars in the F-word jar even when she was gone was sweet, and it was really obvious he would just accept he loved Layla and plan the next step with such a casual manner and attitude. Like Cal, Fox is a man simply born to commit and create a family, but, unlike his pal, he didn't freak out first chance he got, instead he embraced it and just went for it, in his all-optimistic and sunny way. His fights with Layla were extremely "real", like they were a real-life couple, not a fictional one, and his boyish ways of fixing things were cute to the extreme! Also, for some reason I kept picturing Christopher Gorham in his place, and that made him even cuter!<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380405275i/789286._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> The perk of having his "pride" restored quickly because of his link with everything that's going on at Hawkins Hollow was totally childish on behalf of the writer, I admit, but it brought me to laughing tears, especially when Cybil was acting like a girl who never gets the candy after Layla and Quinn had both tried it out. And the love scene with Fox connecting his mind with Layla? God, talk about super hot, with the possibility of getting burned from the heat!<br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1380405275ra/789287.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Personal favorite scene of the book? Cybil running over Twisse's demon dog form with Quinn's car, and being so cool about it! Go, girl! And now that she and Gage are next to play, I wonder how they can handle it, seeing as they're both sworn singles and cynical beyond belief...<br><br><i>Exhausted, content, he walked with her behind the others on a path spattered with moonlight. They’d made magic tonight, he thought. They’d chosen their path, and found their way.<br>The rest was just details.</i><br></span>
  <a data-text-id="5468919699865245542" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

